GIs' Human Rights Abuse Flailed 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, May 17 (KCNA) -- The (south) Korean Federation of Women's Organizations, the Council for Solving the Issue of Volunteers' Corps, the Women's Society for Peace, the Sisterhood Society and other women's organizations of south Korea reportedly called a press conference in Seoul on May 12 to denounce U.S. soldiers' anti-human right war crimes and demand the withdrawal of south Korea's decision on troop dispatch to Iraq.
 The speakers at the press conference said Bush should be brought to the court of human rights for having fostered and connived at brutal sexual maltreatment of Iraqi prisoners by U.S. troops and their crimes against humanity. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Stating that young people must never be sent to the battlefield in Iraq where all manner of dastardly crimes were being committed, they urged the National Assembly not to fail to retract the decision on troop dispatch to Iraq. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Former "comfort women" for the Japanese Imperial Army who were present at the press conference said they could never tolerate the violence and sexual maltreatment against woman by U.S. troops, and declared: "We denounce the anti-human right nature of the Iraqi war and all the wars which reduce women to sex slaves." &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The joint statement read at the press conference voiced opposition to all forms of war that give rise to anti-human right violence against women, children and prisoners, strongly demanding a fundamental policy for protecting the human rights and measures for restoring the victims to their original status in the POW issue, punishment of those responsible, stop to the war and an immediate withdrawal of the planned dispatch of troops to Iraq which would mean siding with anti-human right violence.

Withdrawal of Decision on Troop Dispatch to Iraq Urged 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, May 17 (KCNA) -- Barbarous and nasty manhandling of Iraqi prisoners by U.S. imperialist aggression troops are being disclosed in an unbroken chain these days, creating quite a stir in the international community.
 It must not go unnoticed that these beastly barbarities are not committed by a few brutes of the occupation forces but are organized crimes committed on the instructions of the occupation authorities. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 A news analyst of Rodong Sinmun Monday says in this connection: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It would be an act challenging the entire Korean nation, human conscience and justice for the south Korean authorities to send their young people to Iraq when the cursed murder of Iraqi civilians and manhandling of prisoners by the U.S. imperialists have become a target of protest and denunciation, looming up as a grave problem on the international scene. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
It has become clear that the U.S. war against Iraq is a war of aggression without any justification and, to cap it all, the inhuman maltreatment of prisoners by the occupation troops has been brought to the open to call forth protest and denunciation not only in Iraq but all over the world. It is self-evident where the troop dispatch would lead under this situation. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
The south Korean authorities and political circles, responding to the demand of the whole nation, should promptly abandon the planned troop dispatch to Iraq which would invite unpredictable sacrifices and worldwide denunciation and should retract the decision on troop dispatch itself  The election to the 17th "National Assembly" in south Korea clearly showed what doom awaited the traitors estranged from public sentiments. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is high time the south Korean authorities and political parties made a right option, squarely facing up to the trend of the times and public feelings.

National Cooperation against U.S. Called for 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, May 17 (KCNA) -- The Central Committee of the South Korean Federation of University Student Councils (Hanchongryon) reportedly issued an appeal on May 11 calling on the students to launch a bold struggle against the U.S. domination and interference in order to open a new chapter for independence, democracy and reunification.
 Calling for bringing about a turning phase in the movement for independent reunification by the concerted efforts of the Korean nation, the appeal said: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Let us solidarize with the People's Action against the Troop Dispatch to Iraq and people from all other walks of life in the actions to check the troop dispatch to Iraq, stage an all-people movement for peace on the Korean peninsula and demonstrate the nation's will on June 12, the day of an all-people action. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Let's step up the grand march for independent reunification under the uplifted banner of the June 15 joint declaration. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is our consistent fighting orientation for this year and steadfast will to pave wide avenue for independent reunification through the building of the structure of the Korean nation's confrontation with the U.S. and thus significantly greet the 60th anniversary of the liberation of Korea. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It called upon Hanchongryon to display the enthusiasm and spirit as a new generation struggling for independent reunification and demonstrate the might of the vanguard in the movement to achieve national cooperation against the U.S. on the occasion of the 4th anniversary of the June 15 joint declaration.

Meeting for Repeal of SL Held in S. Korea 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, May 17 (KCNA) -- The People's Meeting for the Repeal of the "Security Law" in south Korea on May 13 reportedly held a meeting of people for the repeal of the SL to greet the first anniversary of one-man demonstration.
 Present there were victims of the SL and their families. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Kwon O Hon, chairman of the Society for Supporting Prisoners of Conscience of the Family Movement for Realizing Democracy, Pak Sok Un, permanent chairman of the Executive Committee of the National People's Solidarity of south Korea, and others spoke there. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Explaining the reason why the SL should be abolished, they dismissed the law an unrealistic evil law as it listed the north as an "anti-state organization" though many south Koreans travel there after the publication of the June 15 joint declaration. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is a shame to talk about human rights, reunification and democracy without repealing the SL, they said, calling for achieving without fail the goal through a nationwide struggle at a time when there mature subjective and objective conditions for the repeal of the evil law. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 A statement demanding the abolition of the SL was read out at the meeting.

New Drug for Angina Pectoris Developed 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, May 17 (KCNA) -- A drug to treat angina pectoris, which has been regarded as an incurable disease in the world, has been developed in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea.
 It is Astragalus Drug for Angina Pectoris developed by Ri Song Suk, a section chief of the Academy of Koryo Medical Science. Its ingredients are astragalus and other natural Koryo medicinal materials. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is efficacious for all kinds of angina pectoris. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 From five to seven days after angina pectoris patients began taking the drug, their spasm starts to stop and within 30 to 40 days, the patients recover their health completely. There is not reoccurrence of the case.  The drug also lowers blood pressure and improves lipid metabolism disorder. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The efficacy rate is above 90 percent. It, which is also efficacious for myocardial infarction sequela, has no side-effect. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
  The drug has been taken by an increasing number of angina pectoris patients.

Film Show Held
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, May 17 (KCNA) -- A film show was held under the sponsorship of the Committee for Cultural Relations with Foreign Countries on Monday on the occasion of the week of the DPRK-Iran friendship.
 Present there on invitation were Iranian Ambassador to the DPRK Jalaleddin Namini Mianji and staff members of his embassy here. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Present were Jon Yong Jin, vice-chairman of the committee who is vice-chairman of the DPRK-Iran Friendship Association, and other officials concerned. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The participants saw an Iranian feature film.

7th Pyongyang Internat'l Commodity Exhibition Opens
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, May 17 (KCNA) -- The 7th Pyongyang International Commodity Exhibition opened at the Three Revolution Exhibition Monday.
 The opening ceremony was attended by officials concerned and delegations of the DPRK and from different countries and regions. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Diplomatic envoys of China, Russia and Syria and staff members of different embassies here were also present there. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Rim Kyong Man, minister of Foreign Trade, made a congratulatory address which was followed by an opening speech by Ri Su Dok, director of the Korean International Exhibition Corporation. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The speakers said that the exhibition would offer an occasion of boosting the friendship and cooperation among countries and people, promoting common progress and prosperity and intensifying multi-faceted exchange, cooperation and trade in keeping with the desire and demand of humankind. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They hoped that the participants in the exhibition would achieve great success through wide-range contacts and diverse trade. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They said that the DPRK would strive hard to strengthen friendship and solidarity and develop cooperation and exchange with all the countries that are friendly to the DPRK in the idea of independence, peace and friendship, and promote common interests and prosperity of the world people. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Prior to the ceremony, the participants laid floral baskets before a photograph of President Kim Il Sung standing with leader Kim Jong Il in the exhibition hall before paying tribute to them. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They went round equipment and materials for the fields of power, metal, light industry and agriculture, electronic products, a variety of daily necessities and other exhibits presented by companies in the DPRK, China, Syria, Thailand, Italy, Malaysia and Taipei, China. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 A reception was held at Yanggakdo International Hotel Monday evening in connection with the opening of the exhibition.
